					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/warpzone" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(147364); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=147364&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610205815" alt="WarpZone" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=147364)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/warpzone" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(147364); return false;" >WarpZone</a></span> <span class="odate time_1355762344 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">17 Dec 2012 16:39</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-1655975">
									

<p>Personally I thought this was decent. The constant references to Site-19 make it &quot;important enough&quot; to be SCP-001 in my opinion. I don't know about making it the &quot;de-facto location&quot; for keter and euclid class objects. A lot of objects of these classes reference Site-19 in their write-up, sure, but a lot of them don't. Doesn't the importance of keeping dangerous SCPs separated make the existence of a de-facto facility kind of a dumb idea? Doesn't the fact that it moves around randomly make things just as difficult for the defenders as it would for would-be attackers?</p>
<p>I also don't think that drugging the food and water with generic prescription antidepressants is such a good idea. Yes, they are hella overprescribed in the real world. No, you don't just give them out like halloween candy to researchers and guards who need <em>clear heads</em> to do their jobs. These drugs have very real side-effects, especially if you happen to give them to people whose neurology doesn't respond to them in the usual way.</p>
<p>All of that said, I like the general concept of 001 being site-19. It seems to totally warrant the security clearance level and the 001 spot on the list. Upvoted on the general strength of the idea, with the caveat that the things I complained about in this post could use some tweaking or rewording.</p>
<p>Also: What does LOST have to do with anything? Is site 19 an island? Was there a plane crash? Does the tone of the article change at the last second and leave you disappointed and convinced the author just didn't have an ending to begin with? No. The similarities are superficial. Deal with it. I could go through every single SCP and cite something else that did the same basic idea already. SIMPSONS DID IT!!!</p>

							</div>

								
					
